    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>

                <p>I have just time to thank you for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> favor; &amp; to
                    beg y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> corrections of <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0209">my map</title></bibl> as soon as convenient. as to
                    <persName ref="pe0054">Col. Roys</persName> I would by no means have anything
                    taken from his by stealth as it is a private property &amp; even
                        unpublished.<note type="editorial">Most likely a reference to proofs of
                        William Roy's <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0140">'Mappa Britanniae
                                Septentrionalis'</title></bibl>, not published until it appeared in
                            his posthumous <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0202"><hi rend="italic">Military Antiquities of the Romans in North
                                Britain</hi></title> (1793)</bibl>. See Pennant's letter to Paton on
                        26 July 1774 and notes.</note> It would be dishonorable to think of it. My
                    outline is from <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0126">Dorret</title></bibl>; but <placeName ref="pl0708">the islands</placeName> are
                    often mended. The <placeName ref="pl0701">orkneys</placeName> from <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0098">Mackenzie</title></bibl>.</p>
                <closer><salute>I am D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sir <lb/>your faithful humble
                            Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi></salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName></signed>
                <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> Aug. 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1776.</dateline></closer>

            </div>
        </body>
